  "decision_notes": "The problem is decomposed into checking the existence of k(n)=1 (powers of 2) and then checking for k(n)=2 (sums of two powers of 2) using modular arithmetic and order theory.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "Determine if there exists an integer n such that 2023*n is a power of 2. If not, investigate the prime factorization of 2023 to explain why k(n) must be greater than 1."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_2",
      "instructions": "Test the possibility of k(n)=2. This requires checking if 2023 divides 2^a + 2^b for some integers a, b. Specifically, determine if there exists an integer m such that 2^m ≡ -1 (mod 2023) or if 2^a ≡ -2^b (mod 2023) is possible. If k(n)=2 is impossible, investigate if k(n)=3 is possible by checking if 2023 divides 2^a + 2^b + 2^c."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent will take the result from helper_1 to establish that k(n) > 1. Then, it will use the result from helper_2 to determine if k(n)=2 is achievable. If helper_2 finds k(n)=2 is impossible, the parent will use the findings for k(n)=3 to conclude the minimum value."
}
```

